ascents.comment: First 4!
Slab of Steak is pretty fun.
Most importantly, this was the only send of the day.  Moral went up.
Would be less frustrating if someone put bigger footholds.
First 3 in Bishop.  Made me feel strong.
Only cheesegrated off once so that was nice.
First climb in Bishop- super fun
Top out nipple is a savior.
Made me stronger than Guim.
Left some blood for future climbers to enjoy.
Top out was fun.
...definitely not a 5
Fun highball
This climb made me fell stylish.  At least more stylish than Pinchy.
First V3 Flash!
One-eye-swollen shut FA
Took less go's than David. Favorite climb
Crimp beta
All 6 spotters were necessary.
Remembered my password finally.
Just needed a little extra gas to get the flash!
Mental note- be more flexible
First 5! After hiking through a foot of snow...not bad
Got it before the boys.
Felt way easier this year!
3rd go, fun problem
Would be more fun if I didn't have to use my knee.
First go this year.
Major lockoffs
Revenge! No tree root will take me out.

ascents.zlaggableName: Bert & Ernie Were Just Good Friends

ascents.comment: Well, at least I did it.
Reachy but very fun
Super fun climb with a suspenseful slab topout
Tell Chris I sent
1 go/day is a good way to work on this
The topout is NOT a gimme, as proven by working 2 years on this.
Now one of my favorite climbs in Bishop!
4 seems to have broken but use the cross beta for the sloper move to make this v2.
Using the right holds helps. First 6!
Dyno goes!
high ball grade
Coolest dihedral I've climbed. Feels hard if you haven't climbed in 2 months.
Aptly named. One of my ugliest top outs ever. Also, do not recommend as warm up.
High heel hooks really bring out my graceful flexibility.
Pretty hard 3, or maybe that's the 2-months-off talking.
Bit of a highball, definitely worth it!
Foot slipped on the start hold...count it as a flash? Also, would be smart to leave someone on the ground to find the downclimb.
So much quality in one problem! Actually trying was key here.
Reachy and beachy
Double foot cut is the way to go
Super knobby black magic of Tuolumne
This is literally the downclimb to the boulder. One move to a jug and then just top out on more jugs. Climbing back down was harder and more interesting.

Note: Do this every time you come here so that you are reminded that no matter how strong you are and how much training you do, you will always be worse than the original Yosemite climbers. Really cool, humbling slab.  Use a high left foot and smear right foot up to get to good crimp.

(Stand) Started two moves before the jug rail.  Pretty fun movement to the rail, cross right to bad 3 finger crimp then use a high heel to lock off to the lip. Don't know why Matt thought it was hard but it made me not feel threatened by him because the flash proved I could definitely take him.
Why is this one of the most popular on Mountain Project? One move to a decent sloper then a big move to another ok sloper then just high right foot to pull up to the top out.

Amazing climb. The physical crux was keeping my feet on the start holds; mental crux was pulling onto the wet slab for the top out.  The Elvis leg made an appearance but I persevered. Note: Repeat without being scared!
Cool feature arete traverse. Only had issues with it because I wasn't short, obviously

Moves are probably more like v5 but I'll take it!  Really fun, tall climb.  Used a right heel to start.  Make sure to use the right crimp for the top out.  Falling in love with Yosemite one climb at a time!

Although sadly the only send of the trip for me, it was exactly what I like in a climb: high slab/face, good movement, top's-a-snow-filled-jug.  Took a fall from the top once, then over compensated with a dead point for the send. Happy 2016!

After falling off the top out too many times, finally figured out how to use my hands and feet to finish this! My Valentine's weekend gift to myself. Used the jump/lunge beta and it felt much easier this time. Also thanks Mom for coming out this weekend!
Thank you left hamstring for healing as a heel hook is definitely necessary. After all the hype, I didn't want to be disappointed; turned out to be even better than expected.
Thanks Josh for coaching me through this! Got it first go this time after trying it in the dark a few months ago. Stunning climb. The next challenge will be going for the repeat.
Possibly the hardest I've ever tried on any problem ever. I'd actually put this in the v8 range. And it gave me bruises, scrapes, and elbow tendinitis (fitting).

This was the first 5 I ever tried, and seeing as I was climbing v3 at the time, I threw up in my mouth at the thought of using the gaston and wrote it off completely. But a few years and  muscles later, I discovered the gaston is actually  way easier and it went on my second go using it. First send after an epic 9 hour drive by Scott involving passionate skill vs. athleticism debates, friendly fighting, and face swaps.

Soft 2nd go. Just kidding, soft epic 1000th go. Holy crap finally put Rene in her place after dragging pads and spotters up here an excessive number of times. I don't think I've ever been so annoyed with a rock and I will definitely be back, but only to poop on her. I might have enjoyed this climb but I have touched it too many times, so fuck Rene.
Fun knee bar for the start.  Stupid name.
Aestheticism, athleticism, and skill at its finest. Gorgeous and fun climb.
Cool lie back
Send Cookies! Don't dab.
Last send of a 40 pt. day! SB North won the day with about 150 pts. Use of a toe hook directly under the butt to bump up the heel is the only way to do the mantle cleanly.
One of many sends on the warm-up boulder.  Sandbox crew crushed it.

Although I started two moves before the actual start holds, I'd still say it goes at v5.  Used a high foot on the big rail out right to lock off to the sidepull crimps.  Took a rest, then smeared up with the undercling for the finish.
V3 Slab in Joe's < V1 Slab in Yosemite
Getting my slab game on on a blizzardy rest day.
More slab in the snow. Watch out for surprise poops in the area. You never know when they might pop out.
Not the best warm up, but had an enjoyable toe hook and standup/dead point move.
Cool first climb in Joe's. Spicy topout that Kelsey made look easy!
Grovely top out but fun climb.
So. Much. Fun. Apparently I can do compression because this only took me a few burns.  Scott helped de-grovel the top out with the left heel hook beta.
Bit technical...and then massive jug gaston.
Exhaustion set in at this point but this climb kinda sucks.  First move is weird, and all the rest are soft.
Fun roof/arete climb. Top out was easy.
Getting lost hiking was a blessing in disguise. Ended up finding this kooky  roof tufa. 10/10 would knee-bar again.
Flash train with Kelsey, Ryan, and Scott after hiking around and finding chossy highballs.
Good holds, good climb. Last send train of the trip.
Cruxy top out! Almost busted my weird tendon/hand on this but it was worth it.
Was way too tired to flash but mflash the next day. Didn't know the PG setters set at Joe's too!
Nice big dead point (well, big for me) was easier than using the pockets.  Still pretty fun.  Good to finally touch real rocks again this weekend.
Actually did this like 2 or 3 years ago.  Almost punted.

Super fun climbing into a mildly chossy topout. All it required was a 1.5 hour hike lost in Undiscovered Country and getting stronger.  For once, my beta was dialed and the send ensued. Shoutout to my climbing journal for helping my terrible memory.
Movement so nice, I did it twice. Way to go LIB and Peter Punter or whatever your name is on 8a for getting a 4/6 on the send to burn ratio. Great beta from David made this oh so soft.

After an initial punt, multiple heel hooks, toe hooks, and double leg wrap made this go. Really fun and unique climb.  Also it wouldn't be a climbing trip without busting a hammy or tendon, so thanks to this climb for completing the trip.
ascents.zlaggableName: Standing On The Head Of The Dragon

ascents.comment: Probably an 8 on the JDS (Jqee dyno scale).  Disclaimer: Most dynos do not register on the scale because they are impossible.

Go right from the start of Four Horsemen for a stellar butt-dragging, 3-finger-crimp-matching v4. The fun toe hook/heel hook switch made up for the fact that my feet were essentially on the ground the whole time.
Boulder 1 near Medlicot. Cool problem. How did the OG climbers keep track of climbs if all the boulders are named "Boulder *number*" and climbs "Unnamed V*grade*"?

Fun 4 starting at Detached.  Work up the arete for a graceful beach whale and then drop off.  5 stars. Provided entertainment while watching Ryan and Chase try to send and discussing Scott's allergy to black cats.
Unnamed V3 on the knob boulder.  Fun little rail thing.  So proud of Cassie for getting her first 3 on her first trip outside!
Next to the Unnamed 4 on Boulder 1.  Good luck finding that.  Has a fun right heel hook move.
I guess my hand/wrist/tendon spasm strain is healing up because this felt pretty easy. Fun little problem. Feels like the sit adds 3 grades.
Oh yeah highballs with chossy top outs! Good to get out despite an epically hot summer. Thanks for the "I think you can't do that" encouragement.
Well, it gives you something to do when you have no pads and are recovering from epic 10b run out slab climbs.
Only counting this for the extra flash points. In reality, the boulder was about 5 feet shorter than in the book (due to sand) and I didn't top out direct.
The first of several underclings to mess of up wrist.  Somewhat enjoyable.
Possibly my proudest send of the weekend.  Start low, then get lower, lie down, then huck your legs over the top and roll over. Birthday girl Dorian crushed this highball!
Still can't do the first move to get my extra point, but at least my hand is healing up so I could do this. For being the namesake of this boulder, I wasn't too psyched on this.
Fun slab.  No pad so I'm not a bitch like Ryan. Weird sequence to pull on though.

After an hour of wandering through the woods, we finally found this boulder as the sun was setting. The first few moves of the climb were fun and promised to make a solid 3 star line, but the top awkward gaston/lunges didn't deliver.
Bit technical for sure, but not all that great.
Why is this in the book?  Maybe 2 stars if you've never climbed anything else in your life.
Cool arete with a scary move near the top
Psyched on my first 6 flash, but I guess that means it's soft.  Still pretty fun.  Thanks for the beta Shirley.
One of my favorites in Tuolumne. Big move from the start to the jug is the way to go.  Confirmation that I still love juggy highballs!
(v5) Dustin's double heel hook match beta was the way to go.  The big move was still hard. Great end to an awesome weekend!
Thought this was pretty tricky, but the downclimb was still the crux.
Blew the flash unfortunately.  The crux was easy with a high right foot/drop knee situation.  More impressive was Dustin's and Chase's Fireball fueled ascents throughout the day.
Started the Bishop season with a Sad's night session. High heel beta and a right hand throw to the meathook gave Chase, Andrew, Kenny, and Michael the send.

Finally got to try this and it went 3rd go! Super fun climb but a little scary to lunge to the pinch. Good end to our Sad's night session after driving 7 hours and meeting Cassie. I didn't tear my rotator cuff or sprain my ankle so this couldn't have gone better.
Easy highballs- my favorite type of climb. Fun to send train with the big crew.

I couldn't get the jump so I used an index finger in the mono, 3 fingers in the left crimp and locked off with a right foot smear to the top. I was so surprised it worked that I literally laughed when I stuck it. Shoutout to Andrew for his first 6! And Matt for flashing while sick.

Went 4th go!  Just kidding. This has been 1.5 years, 60+ burns, and several cases of whiplash in the making. After sending from the second move more than a year ago, I never was able to do it again from the start.  Finally went with a static reach to the bottom part of the Hulk hold in 80 degree heat, and feeling a lot better on the pinch didn't hurt either. I don't know if I've ever felt more satisfied than when I was sitting on the top of this rock.
Ok highball 2

Really felt the last month of no climbing on this one. Usually good crimp face climbing is my jam, but this time, I really jellied off the holds too many times before sending. Felt hard for me but was a great climb.
Poop climb. Literally had to poop on the tablelands after this send.
Why doesn't everyone just lock off the mono? It's good!
ascents.zlaggableName: Whiskey, beer, and spliff hits for breakfast

ascents.comment: I first tried this oh maybe 6 years ago. Mainly, it was so fun to project, I never wanted to send. Unfortunately, my instinctual rt. knee placement allowed me to actually complete the climb.
Did some sort of variation where I just locked off to the top. Maybe a v2 version? Slippery foot though.
Disappointingly did not flash but did send train.
An epic name that is disproportional to the height and quality of this climb. First move static with a semi left drop knee move.
Back to the boulders at last. Checked out a new area, but most of the climbs had better names than moves. Lowball super soft traverse with mediocre movement.

That was unexpected! Another fun climb I never knew existed - compression and body tension on ergonomic holds. Very kind to my baby soft skin, and I always love a boulder that tops out on the tablelands. Great end to a great weekend #sponsoredbyCOVID19. Looking forward to a quarantine cleanse after too much fun with friends.

Guess I'll try this whole climbing outside thing out again for an awesome reunion weekend in Bishop. We all rallied around sending this lesser known problem's jump / stand-on-David's-overly-willing-body start. The super windy conditions helped make these crystals feel great! Fun problem with several possible beta options.
Couple of meh moves on crimps to the jug lip. Working the 7 next to this is more enjoyable.
Not the worst thing I've climbed

Couple of hardish moves to get setup to take on the slab. The slab is tall, but very easy. Unfortunately, this also seems to be the down climb, so I almost had to permanently live on top of this boulder.
Flash train with Jenny and Michael. Cool arete, pretty easy. Downclimb on slab was scary.
